abstract: Mr. Gorbachev was charming and presented himself as a modernizer, but neither Ronald Reagan nor George Bush was convinced he was for real. They would both be proved wrong.
snippet: Mr. Gorbachev was charming and presented himself as a modernizer, but neither Ronald Reagan nor George Bush was convinced he was for real. They would both be proved wrong.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For his first four years in office, President Ronald Reagan had a tough time forging any kind of relationship with his counterparts in the Soviet Union. “They kept dying on me,” he later explained. It fell to his vice president, George H.W. Bush, to attend the funerals. “You die, I fly” became Bush’s wry motto.

main: How Reagan and Bush Overcame Skepticism to Collaborate With Gorbachev
print_headline: How Reagan and Bush Went From Skepticism to Solidarity

abstract: Mr. Hanssen was sentenced to life in prison in 2002, bringing to a close one of the most lurid and damaging espionage cases in American history.
snippet: Mr. Hanssen was sentenced to life in prison in 2002, bringing to a close one of the most lurid and damaging espionage cases in American history.
lead_paragraph: Robert P. Hanssen, a former F.B.I. agent who spied for Moscow off and on for more than two decades during and after the Cold War in one of the most damaging espionage cases in American history, was discovered dead in his prison cell in Colorado on Monday, federal authorities announced. He was 79.

main: Robert Hanssen, F.B.I. Agent Exposed as Spy for Moscow, Dies at 79
print_headline: Robert Hanssen, Double Agent Who Sold Secrets to Moscow, Dies at 79

abstract: In his debut novel, “The New Life,” Tom Crewe reimagines the lives of two pioneers who studied, and supported, homosexuality in 19th-century England.
snippet: In his debut novel, “The New Life,” Tom Crewe reimagines the lives of two pioneers who studied, and supported, homosexuality in 19th-century England.
lead_paragraph: Tom Crewe’s intricate and finely crafted debut novel makes fiction of real history: In London, in the 1890s, two men, John Addington Symonds and Henry Havelock Ellis, collaborated on a study supporting freedom for “sexual inverts,” or what we would now call gay rights. Their efforts predate popular conceptions of the fight for equal rights, and it’s their lives and work that take the spotlight in Crewe’s reimagining.

main: The Gay Rights Movement Before the Gay Rights Movement

main: Disinformation Has Become Another Untouchable Problem in Washington

abstract: In “Cinema Speculation,” the filmmaker recalls his glory days of moviegoing.
snippet: In “Cinema Speculation,” the filmmaker recalls his glory days of moviegoing.
lead_paragraph: Most film directors would no more comment on one another’s movies than they would score each other’s performance in bed. Filmmaking is a collaborative art but directors rarely get to collaborate with one another, and so frequently combine rabid curiosity about each other’s working methods with the slight fear they might be doing it wrong, while maintaining a facade of polite praise for the result. Then there is the Quentin Tarantino approach.

main: Quentin Tarantino’s Greatest Hits of the ’70s

abstract: The Revolutionary Guards — the country’s most powerful military force — have become so deeply woven into Iran’s economy and power structure that they have everything to lose if the system falls.
snippet: The Revolutionary Guards — the country’s most powerful military force — have become so deeply woven into Iran’s economy and power structure that they have everything to lose if the system falls.
lead_paragraph: The intensity of protests that have swept Iran over the past month, with calls to topple the Islamic Republic, have shaken the state. But in some ways, the country’s authoritarian clerical rulers have been preparing for this moment since the 1979 Islamic Revolution, which established a conservative theocracy that has held firm until today.

main: Iran’s Loyal Security Forces Protect Ruling System That Protesters Want to Topple
print_headline: Tehran’s Most Loyal Defenders Have Much to Lose in Protests
